<H3>WBArmy</H3>
<P>
Every Amiga user who likes to play might know Scorched Tanks. This is a light 
version for the workbench.
</P>
<P>
&#132;Light&#132; means less graphics, less weapons, less opponents.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately the game can only be played on a 640*512 screen or higher, my 
eyes don앖 like it...
</P>
<P>
But a really Amiga freak has an eye friendly monitor, and don앖 think it is a 
negative point ;-)
</P>
<P>
The aim of the game is to shoot the opponents tank.
</P>
<P>
You fix the firing angle, strength and size of the munition. Better munition can be 
bought in a shop (also during the game). Further more you can move your tank 
(with petrol from the shop) and buy additional energy.
</P>
<P>
To make a good shot you have to take notice of the wind which changes every 
round, in strength and direction.
</P>
<P>
And so it is not as easy as it seams.
</P>
<P>
If the computer opponent is not smart ( or to smart) you can change the artificial 
intelligenz ( or imbecility), just as you want.
</P>
<P>
Further more you can decide how much bonus boxes should fall down, which color 
the background should have, the maximum of the getable energy, if there is wind 
and so on...
</P>
<P>
The graphic is quite simple, normal for a WB Game. There is not much sound, the 
best one can be heard by shooting out of the screen.
</P>
<P>
Sum: without regard to sound and graphic, it is a good alternative to Scorched 
Tanks, but the original is much better.
</P>
<P>
The one who wants real action should decide to get the commercial version Worms 
DC.
</P>
